      <div class="content">

        <p class="lead">
          I am a <strong>software engineer</strong> living in <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=Dallas" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="pokhara-link">Dallas, Texas</a>. Every day I pick up a new idea, try it out, break something, fix it, and learn a little more. I write blog posts about the things I learn along the way. That process of learning, making mistakes, and figuring things out is what I love most about this work.
        </p>

        <h2>How It All Started</h2>
        <p>
          My story with computers started when I was about 10 years old. I grew up in a small town in <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=Nepal" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="nepal">ðŸ‡³ðŸ‡µ</a> and my mom got me into a private school that had a small computer lab. There were only a few old computers in that room. But to me, it felt like magic. I remember sitting there and just staring at the screen, wondering what these machines could really do.
        </p>
        <p>
          After finishing high school in <a href="https://www.google.com/search?q=pokhara+nepal" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="pokhara-link">Pokhara</a>, I decided to move to the United States to study computer science. My parents believed in me and made it possible. I will never be able to thank them enough. In 2016, I arrived in Chicago at 19. I was full of hope but also very scared. I had big dreams and no real idea of what was ahead of me.
        </p>
        <p>
          I finished my Bachelor's degree in 2021 and my Master's degree in 2025, both in Computer Science from the <a href="https://www.unt.edu/index.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="unt-link">University of North Texas</a>. School taught me the basics and how to think. But my real learning came from sitting alone at my computer, trying things, breaking things, getting stuck for hours, and slowly figuring it out. One small step at a time.
        </p>

        <h2>My Path as a Developer</h2>
        <p>
          The first programming language I learned was <strong>C</strong>. Then I found <strong>Java</strong> and something clicked. I really enjoyed it and I still enjoy working with it today.
        </p>
        <p>Over the years I have worked with:</p>
        <div class="skill-chips">
          <span>Java &amp; Spring Boot</span>
          <span>Microservices</span>
          <span>Backend Systems</span>
          <span>React</span>
          <span>Machine Learning &amp; AI</span>
          <span>DevOps &amp; Containers</span>
          <span>Kubernetes</span>
          <span>AWS</span>
        </div>
        <p>
          These days I mostly work with <em>TypeScript</em>, <em>Spring Boot</em>, <em>PostgreSQL</em>, <em>Docker</em>, <em>Testcontainers</em>, and <em>Kubernetes</em>. I am still learning better ways to use all of them. It is a slow and ongoing process.
        </p>
        <p>
          One of my early goals was to work at a big company and build things that real people use. In 2021, I got that chance when <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/American_Express" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer" class="amex-link">American Express</a> hired me as a Software Engineer. It felt like a dream. Some days I still feel very lucky.
        </p>
        <p>
          But what keeps me going is not the job title or the company name. It is something much simpler. It is finally understanding something that confused you yesterday. It is fixing a bug and learning why it happened. Small things like that. I think this is true for life too. You do not always need big wins. Sometimes one small step forward is enough.
        </p>

        <h2>Life Outside Tech</h2>
        <p>
          Outside of work, I like to keep things simple. I go for walks or run early in the morning when it is still quiet. It helps me clear my head before the day starts. Sometimes I find the best solutions to problems during those walks, when I am not even thinking about work.
        </p>

        <h2>What I Believe</h2>
        <p>I do not have any big philosophies. Just a few simple things I try to follow:</p>
        <ul>
          <li>Work hard even when it is difficult</li>
          <li>Be honest with yourself about what you know and what you still need to learn</li>
          <li>The rest you figure out along the way</li>
        </ul>
        <p>
          I have not done anything special yet. But getting to where I am today took a lot of time, patience, and support from my family. I left home, moved to a new country, and slowly found my way in this field. I think many people know that feeling of just trying to make a little progress each day without knowing if you are doing it right.
        </p>
        <p>
          If you are reading this, I hope it gives you something. Maybe just a small reminder that someone else is out there learning too, making mistakes, and trying to get better.
        </p>
        <p>
          And if you feel like you are just figuring it out as you go, same here. I think most of us are. You are not alone in that.
        </p>

